introduction.p:
Equivalently,
if we want to consider the average rate of change of f on [a,b],
we compute

  AV_{[a,b]} = \frac{f(b)-f(a)}{b-a}
.

ul.li:
The derivative is a generalization of the instantaneous velocity of a position function:
if y = s(t) is the position function of a moving object,
s'(a) tells us the instantaneous velocity of the object at time t=a.

solution.p:
From the limit definition, we know that

  f'(2) = \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{f(2+h)-f(2)}{h}
.

Combining like terms, we have

  f'(2) = \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{ -3h - h^2}{h}
.

ol.li:
The average rate of change on [1,4] is \frac{f(4)-f(1)}{4-1} = \frac{-5 - 1}{3} = -2.
Similar calculations show the average rate of change on [3,7] is also -2.
On [5,5+h], observe that

  \frac{f(5+h)-f(5)}{h} \amp = \frac{(3-2(5+h)) - (3-10)}{h}
  \amp = \frac{3 - 10 - 2h + 7}{h}
  \amp = \frac{-2h}{h}
  \amp = -2
.

Using the limit definition of the derivative, we find that

  f'(1) = \amp  \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{f(1+h) - f(1)}{h}
  = \amp  \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{(3 - 2(1+h)) - (3-2)}{h}
  = \amp  \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{3 - 2 - 2h - 1}{h}
  = \amp  \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{-2h}{h}
  = \amp  \lim_{h \to 0} -2
  = \amp  -2
.

s'(a) is positive whenever 0 \le a \lt \frac{1}{2};
s'(a) is negative whenever
\frac{1}{2} \lt a \lt 2;
s'(\frac{1}{2}) = 0.

li.p:
AV_{[0,7]}=\frac{0.1175}{7} \approx 0.01679 billion people per year;
P'(7) \approx 0.1762 billion people per year;
P'(7) \gt AV_{[0,7]}.

We will say that today's date is July 1, 2015,
which means that t = 22.5;

  P'(22.5) = \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{115(1.014)^{22.5+h}-115(1.014)^{22.5}}{h};

P'(22.5) \approx 0.02186 billions of people per year.

Finally, we verify these approximations using an algebraic approach.
The definition of the derivative of f at x=a shows that

  f'(2) &= \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{f(2+h)-f(2)}{h}
  &= \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{\left[(2+h)^2 - 3(2+h)\right] - (-2)}{h}
  &= \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{\left[4+4h+h^2 - 6 - 3h\right] + 2}{h}
  &= \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{h^2 + h}{h}
  &= \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{h(h+1)}{h}
  &= \lim_{h \to 0} h+1
  &= 1

This confirms our conclusions using the numeric and geometric approaches.

Finally, we verify these approximations using an algebraic approach.
The definition of the derivative of f at x=a shows that

  f'(1) &= \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{f(1+h)-f(1)}{h}
  &= \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{\frac{1}{1+h} - 1}{h}
  &= \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{\frac{1}{1+h} - 1}{h} \left(\frac{1+h}{1+h} \right)
  &= \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{1-(1+h)}{h(1+h)}
  &= \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{-h)}{h(1+h)}
  &= \lim_{h \to 0} -\frac{1}{1+h}
  &= -1
.
This confirms our conclusions using the numeric and geometric approaches.

Finally, we verify these approximations using an algebraic approach.
The definition of the derivative of f at x=a shows that

  f'(1) &= \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{f(1+h)-f(1)}{h}
  &= \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{\sqrt{1+h}-\sqrt{1}}{h}
  &= \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{\sqrt{1+h}-1}{h}
  &= \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{\sqrt{1+h}-1}{h} \left(\frac{\sqrt{1+h}+1}{\sqrt{1+h}+1} \right)
  &= \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{(1+h)-1}{h(\sqrt{1+h}+1)}
  &= \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{h}{h(\sqrt{1+h}+1)}
  &= \frac{1}{\sqrt{1+h}+1}
  &= \frac{1}{2}
.
This confirms our conclusions using the numeric and geometric approaches.

Finally, we attempt to verify these approximations using an algebraic approach. Notice first that
\frac{f(\frac{\pi}{2}+h)-f(\frac{\pi}{2})}{h} &= \frac{\sin(\frac{\pi}{2}+h) - \sin \frac{\pi}{2}}{h} &= \frac{\sin(\frac{\pi}{2}+h) - 1}{h}
Using the sum of two angles identity for the sine function, it follows that
\sin(\frac{\pi}{2}+h) = \sin \frac{\pi}{2} \cos(h) + \cos \frac{\pi}{2} \sin(h) = 1 \cdot \cos(h) + 0 \cdot \sin(h) = \cos(h) . Hence,
f'(\frac{\pi}{2}) &= \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{f(\frac{\pi}{2}+h)-f(\frac{\pi}{2})}{h} &= \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{\cos(h) - 1}{h}
At this point, we encounter a limit that we are unable to evaluate further using algebraic means. Like the earlier limit above, we can estimate the limit using small values of h. Doing so confirms that this limit also approaches 0, and we hence conclude that f'(\frac{\pi}{2}) = 0.
